}|CP||ht|d|cp|8|AT|^l@2^Z@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|That was the basic idea behind |CP|1|AT|^*GLEG,IMP Scoring in Team Games^*N|CP||AT|. However, it was decided to use "International Matchpoint Scale" (on the left) in order to lessen the effect of a really bad result. The IMP scale translates absolute scores to a number between 0 and 24. For example, a score difference of 20-40 is 1 IMP, a score difference of 50-80 is 2 IMPS, and so forth. |
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


AT|

In the example in the last panel, +450 translates to 10 IMPs. Without the IMP scale, a score difference of 500 would be 10 times better than a score difference of 50. But with the IMP scale, +50 translates to 2 IMPs while 500 translates to 11 IMPS, so the 500 is 5.5 times better than the 50.|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


AT|

A variant of IMP scoring (Cross - IMP scoring) is used for |cp|1|at|^*GLEG,Pairs Games^*N|cp||at| such as what is done on BBO. Each opponent's score is subtracted from your score and converted to IMPs. The IMPs are then summed and divided by the number of opponents.|
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


HT|s|at|^lNext is an example set of scores of 5 pairs playing the same board.|
pg| ***** 33 ***** |


NT||
%%
qx||HT|b|fp|1|cs|1|cp|4|at|^-{  Cross -IMP Scoring Used in Pair Games }
^-|cp||fp||ht|d|at|^B@2With the help of computers the Cross-IMP scoring is the mainstream now (used at BBO). In Cross-IMP your score on any particular board is compared with those of every other pair sitting in the opposite direction to you, across the field. Using the IMP chart the point difference in each comparison is converted to IMP. The total of these comparisons in IMPs is averaged to give you your score on that board.|
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


AT|

Steps of using this technique are: 
1) Every score on any particular board is compared against every other score for the respective pair. In other words, for every score, the scores of the opponents are subtracted.
2) The subtracted results are converted in IMPs by using International Matchpoint Scale.
3) Using International Matchpoint Scale convert the point differences to IMPs.
4) Average the IMPs which is the score for that pair.|
PG| ***** 35 ***** |


NT||
%%
HT|b|fp|1|cs|1|cp|4|at|^-{  Cross -IMP Scoring Used in Pair Games }
^-|cp||fp||ht|d|at|^B@2In step (1) Let’s assume we have a board played 5 times and the following are the results. Both sides are vulnerable.
NS pair 1 bid and made 4@H for a score of +620
NS pair 2 bid 3@H but ten tricks for a score of +170
NS pair 3 bid and made 3@H for a score of +140
NS pair 4 also bid and made 3@H for a score of +140
NS pair 5 was set by one trick in 4@H for a score of -100|
PG| ***** 36 ***** |


AT|

In step (2) subtract each for opponents' scores from the NS pair 1's score as it was a team match:
A. NS pair 1 score ---> 620 – 170   = 450
B. NS pair 1 score ---> 620 – 140   = 480
C. NS pair 1 score ---> 620 - 140   = 480
D. NS pair 1 score ---> 620 -(-100) = 720|
PG| ***** 37 ***** |


AT|

In step (3) convert the subtractions in IMPs:
For A 450 we have 10 IMP
For B 480 we have 10 IMPs
For C 480 we have 10 IMPs
For C 720 we have 12 IMPs|
PG| ***** 38 ***** |


AT|

For step (4) sum the IMPs up and divide them by the number of opponents (4 here) and the result for the NS pair 1 is (10+10+10+12)/4 = 10.5 IMPs. The EW pair 1, who played this board on the same table with NS pair 1, will receive -10.5 IMPs accordingly.|
PG| ***** 39 ***** |


AT|

Using the same steps the IMP scoring is done for all of the other pairs as shown next.|
PG| ***** 40 ***** |


NT||
%%
HT|b|fp|1|cs|1|cp|4|at|^-{  Cross -IMP Scoring Used in Pair Games }
^-|cp||fp||ht|d|at|^B@2For NS pair 2
A. NS pair 2 score ---> 170 - 620   = -450 -10 IMPs
B. NS pair 2 score ---> 170 - 140   = 30    1 IMPs 
C. NS pair 2 score ---> 170 - 140   = 30    1 IMPs
D. NS pair 2 score ---> 170 - (-100) = 270   7 IMPs
NS pair 2 receives (-10+1+1+7)/4 = -0.25  IMPs. The EW pair 2, who played this board on the same table with NS pair 1, will receive 0.25 IMPs.|
PG| ***** 41 ***** |


AT|

For NS pair 3 
A. NS pair 3 score ---> 140 - 620    = -450 -10 IMPs
B. NS pair 3 score ---> 140 - 170    = -30  -1 IMPs
C. NS pair 3 score ---> 140 - 140    = 0     0 IMPs
D. NS pair 3 score ---> 140 - (-100) = 240   6 IMP
NS pair 3 receives (-10-1+0+6) = -5/4= -2.25 IMPs. The EW pair 3, who played this board on the same table with NS pair 1, will receive 2.25 IMPs.|
PG| ***** 42 ***** |


AT|

For NS pair 4
A. NS pair 4 score ---> 140 - 170    = -30  -1 IMPs
B. NS pair 4 score ---> 140 - 140    = 0     0 IMPs
C. NS pair 4 score ---> 140 - (-100) = 240   6 IMP 
D. NS pair 4 score ---> 140 - (-100) = 240   6 IMP
NS pair 4 receives (-10-1+0+6) = -5/4= -2.25 IMPs
The EW pair 3, who played this board on the same table with NS pair 1, will receive 2.25 IMPs.|
PG| ***** 43 ***** |


AT|

And NS pair 5
A. NS pair 5 score ---> -100 -620= -720 = -12 IMPs
B. NS pair 5 score ---> -100 -170= -270 = -7 IMPs
C. NS pair 5 score ---> -100 -140= -240 = -6 IMPs 
D. NS pair 5 score ---> -100 -140= -240 = -6 IMPs
NS pair 5 receives (-12 -7-6-6)/4  = -7.75 IMPs. The EW pair 5 will receive 7.75 IMPs.|
PG| ***** 44 ***** |


