qx|MP3,Match Point Scoring|cs|1|cp|2|fp|1|at|
^-{  Match Point Scoring by Howard Schutzman  }
^-|HT|d|fp||cs||cp||at|^b@2Match point scoring is what is used in most live pairs games. It works as follows:
^ca. You get 1 point for each pair whose score is worse than yours.
^cb. You get 1/2 point for each pair whose score is tied with yours.

In pair games, your score on a board is usually expressed in the actual number of match points you scored on that board. On BBO, it is expressed as a percentage of the maximum number of match points you could win on the board had your score been the highest. Let me repeat the example I used for IMP scoring, score it using match points, and compare it to the IMP score.|
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


HT|L|AT|Pair ^CContract ^fPoints ^IMPs ^kMP Percentage ^oDetails ^UIMP scores 
1 ^c  4@H ^f620 ^i4 ^k100% ^oBeat 4 pairs ^U10.5
2 ^c  3@H +1 ^f170 ^I3 ^k75% ^OBeat 3 pairs ^U-0.25
3 ^c  3@H ^f140 ^I1.5  ^k37.5% ^OBeat 1 and tied 1 pair ^U-1.25
4 ^c  3@H ^f140 ^I1.5  ^k37.5% ^OBeat 1 and tied 1 pair ^U-1.25
5 ^c  4@H -1 ^f100 ^I0 ^k0%    ^OLost to all ^U-9.75

Here are some conclusions you can draw from the above example:

^c@2The size of your score does not matter, just how many people you do better than. Pair 2 did very well compared to Pairs 3 and 4 despite the fact that their score was only 30 points higher. Similarly, Pair 1 only did a little better than Pair 2 even though their score was 450 points higher.

^c@2Overtricks do matter. Pair 2 did much better than Pairs 3 and 4 by simply making an overtrick.

^c@2Bidding game does not always help as much as in IMPS. Pair 1 would have done almost as well had they been in 3@h making 4 (just like Pair 2).|
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


NT||
%%
cs|1|cp|2|fp|1|at|
^-{  Match Point Scoring by Howard Schutzman  }
^-|HT|d|fp||cs||cp||at|^b@2Let me define some common terms used in Matchpoint scoring:|
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


AT|

^c@2Average – the ## of pairs you did better than was about the same as the ## of pairs who did better than you. Your match point percentage is about 40% - 60%.|
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


AT|

^c@2Average Plus – you did better than a majority of pairs. Your match point percentage is about 65% - 85%.|
PG| ***** 58 ***** |


AT|

^c@2Average Minus – you did not do as well as a majority of pairs. Your match point % is about 15% - 35%.|
PG| ***** 59 ***** |


AT|

^c@2Top – you did better than all pairs, perhaps tieing 1 or 2 at most. Your match point % is about 90% - 100%.|
PG| ***** 60 ***** |


AT|
^c@2Bottom – you did worse than all pairs, perhaps tieing 1 or 2 at most. Your match point percentage is 0%-10%.|
PG| ***** 61 ***** |


AT|

^b@2Although the scores of individual boards are usually described in terms of actual match points (except on BBO where they use match point %), your overall score is usually expressed as a percentage of the theoretical maximum score you can achieve. For example, in an 8 table game with 24 boards, your theoretical maximum is 168 match points (7 match points on each board x 24 boards). If your match point score was 84, that would be a 50% game. A 55+% game is good and should usually earn you some master points. A 60+% game is excellent and will often result in a 1st or 2nd place finish.|
PG| ***** 62 ***** |


AT|

Most expert players prefer IMP scoring to match points. They feel it is a truer test of bridge skill and minimizes luck. I, on the other hand, strongly prefer Matchpoints. I think it a much more interesting form of bridge. Although bridge in any form is never boring, in IMP scoring many hands are inconsequential and you can relax. Even if the declarer or the defense slip a trick, that will only result in a small loss or gain. An IMP match comes down to how well you do on a small minority of crucial boards with big swings. In Matchpoints, on the other hand, every board counts. An overtrick can be crucial. You have to be on your toes on every hand because a small slip can be very costly.
|ht|y|at|Please click |cp|1|at|^*GB,here^*N|CP||AT| to return to the opening page.|
