^-|fp||ht|c|at|^B@2^Z@3Howard did not have enough time to address many of his points and charts or explain some issues as he wanted to. This section is intended to do that. To better understand his tutorial it is important to become familiar with terms and definitions outlined here. As you will notice many of terms in the tutorial are blue hyperlinked and you can get back here and read on more. Some of very obvious definitions are not included. You can get back to the opening page by clicking a blue hyperlink at the bottom of each page.

^*BTrick^*N: It is a ^*Btrick^*N when four cards are played. There are only 13 trick during each deal.

^*BBoard or Deal^*N: The metal or plastic tray that holds the pre-dealt cards. This term also refers to the whole deal itself ("What was our score on Board ##4?" or "We played 26 boards against Joe's team."). 


^*BBook^*N: The first six tricks taken by partnership declaring. Only tricks in excess of book are counted for fulfilling the final contract. To make a contract of 4@S, you must take 10 tricks (6 for book plus the 4@S contract committed). Book also refers to the number of tricks the defenders must win before they can begin earning a score for defeating a contract. If the opponents' contract is 3@D, book for defenders is 4 tricks -- if they take a fifth trick, they defeat declarer's contract and earn a plus score.

^*BPoint^*N: Each trick is assigned a number of points which varies by the suit is awarded to the winning side. The first six tricks do not get any points. They are:
^C@2Each trick in minor suits = 20 points
Each trick in major suits = 30 points
In No-Trump the first trick = 40 points and the rest are 30 points each. 

^B@2^Z@3^*BContract^*N: Is the number of tricks the pair declaring commits to make. The number should be at least 7 (the first six is called the book). The highest number of tricks available in a contract are 13. In addition to the number each contract is in either a suit or in NT. |
