^-|fp||ht|b|va|6|at|^B@2^Z@3^*BContract bridge^*N: Contract bridge, or simply bridge, is a trick-taking game using a standard 52-card deck. It is played by four players in two competing partnerships, with partners sitting opposite each other around a table. Contract bridge gets its name from the fact that on each hand one side enters into a "contract" to take a certain ## of tricks.

^*BDuplicate Bridge^*N: Is a form of contract bridge in which the same hands are played successively by different partnerships. In duplicate bridge, a player normally plays with the same partner (^*BPair Games^*N).

^*BIndividual event^*N: In an individual event, each player is paired with a different partner in each round. Individual events are less popular and much less common than pairs and teams events.

^*BPairs Game^*N: In a pairs game, every pair plays against a number of opposing pairs in successive rounds, depending on the size of the field. The pairs moving from table to table (two pairs for each table) is pre-determined by the number of pairs playing the event. Events with less than 7 tables are usually played as a Mitchell movement. Each North/South pair, while sitting on the same table, plays against all or most East/West pairs who are moving. The usual form of scoring for a pairs tournament is either ^*BMatchpoint^*N or ^*BIMP^*N scoring.

^*BTeams Game^*N: In a Team Tournament, two pairs constitute a team. If there are just two teams, they compete using two tables and having one pair from each team seated at each table, in opposite directions. Teams game are played either as "Swiss teams" or as "knockout events." For Teams Game is IMP scoring is used.

^c@2^*BSwiss Teams^*N: In Swiss events teams (four players in each team) play short matches, usually of seven boards. After seven boards points are converted to IMP using Standard IMP Table, a winner or tie determined and results turned in. The director keeps tabulations of the results and matches teams with similar records for the subsequent round.
|VA|4|at|^c@2^*BKnockout Teams^*N: In this form of scoring two teams play an extended match. At the end of the match points are converted to IMP using Standard IMP Table. Team with the most IMPs wins and goes on to the next round of play. The losing team is eliminated from further competition.

