^-|fp||ht|b|va|6|at|^B@2^Z@3^*BIMP Pairs Cross Scoring^*N: Is a pairs game (used at BBO) with a standard duplicate movement. At the end of the game the total scores for each board are averaged either by Butler method or by Cross-IMP. Each team's individual score is compared to the average. IMPs are awarded or subtracted from a pairs total based on how much over or under average their score is. High IMPs score wins.|
PG| ***** 134 ***** |


AT|

With the help of computers the Cross-IMP scoring is the mainstream now. In Cross-IMP your score on any particular board is compared with those of every other pair sitting in the opposite direction to you, across the field. Using the IMP chart the point difference in each comparison is converted to IMP. The total of these comparisons in IMPs is averaged to give you your score on that board.

Steps of using this technique are: 
1) Every score on any particular board is compared against every other score for the respective pair. In other words, for every score, the scores of the opponents are subtracted.
2) The subtracted results are converted in IMPs by using INTERNATIONAL MATCH POINT SCALE.
3) Using INTERNATIONAL MATCH POINT SCALE convert the point differences to IMPs.
4) Average the IMPs which is the score for that pair.

In step (1) Let’s assume we have a board played 4 times and the following are the results:
NS pair 1: 430
NS pair 2: 400
NS pair 3: 150
NS pair 4: -50|
